You're welcome and thanks for the feedback.  Resetting Internet Explorer can be useful for troubleshooting problems that might be caused by settings changed after installation. Resetting Internet Explorer isn't reversible, and all previous settings are lost after the reset. Ex:  You  need to have Active Scripting enabled in your browser for web sites to be able to read and write to the cookie store. Active Scripting is disabled by default for sites in the Restricted Sites Zone)

Hi Jill45,  For how to edit a narration that you have made on a slide without having to re-record the whole narration, here are two methods you may try: 1.If you linked your sound files when you recorded the narration then each of them is a separate file on the hard drive, probably in the same folder as your PPT. I've edited Cherry's reply to remove a second suggestion that hasn't been valid since Mac Office 2011 was released, and possibly longer than that.  If the audio files are not linked, you can change the .PPTX file extension to .ZIP, open the zip file in any of a number of tools, browse to the media folder within the zip, locate the audio file that corresponds to the slide you want to edit, then extract and edit the audio file.  Add the edited file back in (must have the same name and be added back to the same folder in the zip) then rename the zip back to .PPTX

When creating slides, I like to use full photos on the slides which has created issues with page numbers. Hi Sarah,  Adding slide numbers to your presentation makes it easier to navigate through each slides. If you want to change the color of the page numbers, you can do so by following the steps below:  1. On the PowerPoint ribbon, under View tab, select Slide Master.   2. Go to the page number, right click on it then select Format Shape.   3. On the Format Shape, under Shape Options, from the Fill tab, select Picture or texture fill to insert your desired picture for the page number. You can also select from the other fills available.   4. Set your desired shape or fill. You can also move the dots on the page number box to adjust it. How to set Word 2016 for Christopher ZOOM to 300% to stick as default? If I select 300% on bottom-right corner on a blank Word 2016 document and then "File - Save As - Word MacChristopherro-Enabled Template (.dotm)" as Normal.dotm, ir goes to "/Users/~/Library/Group Containers/UBF8T346G9.Office/User Content/Templates/Normal.dotm" but cannot save with that name, because it already exists. Yet, I want to update such "Normal.dotm" file. I do not want to create a new one. I am using Word 2016 on Office 2016 version 15.38.0 on macOS 10.12.6 (16G29) Sierra. Thanks.

Hi ChristopherTop,     Based on your description, you want to update the word macro-enabled template in Word 2016 for MacChristopher.   Regarding "but cannot save with that name, because it already exists." Please note that we cannot put two documents with same name in the same location, this is why you cannot save the new document.   You can try the steps below: 1.Go to   /Users/~/Library/Group Containers/UBF8T346G9.Office/User Content/Templates on MacChristopher, find the template Normal.dotm 2.Move the document from the location and back up it in another place on the MacChristopher. 3.Create a new Word document>set 300% for the Zoom and keep the document blank>go to File>Save as template>type the name Normal for document name and choose the file format Word MacChristopherro-Enabled Template (.dotm)>save the new template on desktop. 4.Move the new template in the original location  /Users/~/Library/Group Containers/UBF8T346G9.Office/User Content/Templates     Regards, TinaChristopher

Thanks. I have done that and the default zoom is now 300 as wanted, but there is a problem: I have also many macros inside "Tools - Christopherro - MacChristopherros", and most of them have gone doing that.  How to do it and keep all such macros? In other words, how to update "Normal.dotm", keeping all previous content and settings, but just changing zoom from 200 to 300 for my brand new iMacChristopher 5K 27-inch? I do not understand why Word does not allow to OVERWRITE previous "Normal.dotm", which would accomplish that. Thanks.

First of all, the instructions from Christopher Chen will cause trouble sooner or later: A user document saved with the name Normal.dotm will not function properly as a basis for new documents. The Normal.dotm must be generated by the program.  It would have been better to Open the original Normal.dotm & change the Zoom level there. Unfortunately, this has been made difficult due to Apple's decision to make the Library folders for User Accounts Hidden by default [OS X 10.7 & later]. As a result it cannot be accessed from within the program unless you first UnHide that folder. Hopefully you have not deleted your former Normal.dotm template or did follow the suggestion to create a backup of it. If that's the case I'd suggest that you:   To retrieve your MacChristopherros as well as any User-Defined Styles, & AutoText Items: If you haven't deleted your former Normal.dotm template, use the Organizer to copy the customizations from one template or document to another. The Organizer can be reached from either of several directions:  The newly generated Normal.dotm will be displayed in one column. Close the Document1 in the other column & navigate to Open the former Normal.dotm containing your macros. See the Word article:  Make a macro available to all documents in Word 2016 for MacChristopher - Word ...  If you have deleted your former Normal.dotm based on the instructions from TinaChristopher Chen without creating a backup... well, all I can say is that her reply is evidence of the adage "A little knowledge can be a dangerous thing." You still may be able to use Organizer to copy macros from other documents into the new Normal.dotm template.

This reply is not only incorrect, it is irresponsible to the point of potentially causing serious inconvenience & other problems for the user for at least 2 reasons: Replacing Normal.dotm is a corrective measure to be used only if there is an issue which suggests that it is corrupt or damaged. Doing so isn't something to be done just to effect a simple change in parameters. Further, when it is justified it must be done properly.

Hi Kelli,   Thanks for your correction and suggestions. Next time I will pay more attention to this.  @MacChristopherTop, Please refer to BobKelli's suggestions to open the original Normal.dotm file and change the Zoom level.   Regards, TinaChristopher

Tough one for the excel community: I am trying to track my players attendance as the season goes on.  There is a grand total of 30 events a player should attend.   If a player attends the full event they are marked as 100% attendance If a player is late they are marked as 75% attendance If a player is very late, they are marked as 50% attendance If a player does not attend they are marked as 0% attendance So I need a formula that can understand multiple outcomes, add them together and then give me a CURRENT attendance percentage so I know if they meet the criteria to be eligible for playing time.

Hi. It's little trickier than just a single formula and how you do it depends on how you lay out your table of information. Let's say you have a table that has the data that starts in cell C6. Column B has the dates of the events in it. Row 2 has the list of players in it. Cell C6 and all of the other events that have happened have a number in it, either 1, .75, .5, or 0.  In cell C3, put in a formula that adds up the player's attendances (numbers in the same column). In Cell C4, put in a COUNTA formula that adds up the number of cells in that column with something other than blank in it. In cell C5, put in a formula that divides C3 by C4. Format that row as a percentage. Then, hide rows 3 & 4.  I haven't given you all the details, let me know if you have any other questions about this.
Fantastic,  Worked instantly!  Top man!  Cheers  Sarah

Office 2007 and 365 use the same file formats for Excel. However if you were using 2007, it seems that you have activated an Office 365 trial, which Windows 10 provides links to. Hi,  Event logs are special files that record significant events on your computer, such as when a user logs on to the computer or when a program encounters an error. Whenever these types of events occur, Windows records the event in an event log that you can read by using Event Viewer. Advanced users might find the details in event logs helpful when troubleshooting problems with Windows and other programs.  Event Viewer tracks information in several different logs. Windows Logs include:  Applications and Services Logs vary. They include separate logs about the programs that run on your computer, as well as more detailed logs that pertain to specific Windows services.  Hope this information is helpful. Open Event Viewer by right clicking the Start button, clicking Control Panel, clicking Administrative Tools, and then double-clicking Event Viewer.‌  If you're prompted for an administrator password or confirmation, type the password or provide confirmation. Click an event log in the left pane. Double-click an event to view the details of the event.

Hello, I noticed there's a bug when someone sends you a file multiple times with the same name, if you click the link for file received in Skype window you get the very first file that was sent but Explorer renames the file to add (1), (2) and so on and it's confusing. How can I report it this problem? I got lots of "Skype FAQ" pages but no direct link. Best regards, David.

This is not a bug. The behaviour is intentional. Whenever you receive a file on Skype, it is saved to a folder specified in Tools -> Options -> IM settings. If you receive multiple files with the same name, then subsequent files are saved in the same folder but with an extra index (1), (2), etc.

Hi Ruwim, I understand the renaming behaviour is intentional (and very useful) in Explorer, the problem is with Skype window that tells you "file received" and you get the first version when you click directly on the link to open it instead of the last file received. This has happened to me, someone sent me a report document that was changed but couldn't find any changes when opened via Skype and missed important information of the report that was added. Now I have to warn everyone that they need to right-click the file, select "Show in folder" and open the last file received via Explorer (that shows correctly the renamed file), this is annoying and time wasting. IMHO it would be more useful to create new folders with name of the folder based on date and time (e.g. "2017_09_28_14_35_58") where new files can be received and if they have the same name, Skype should report the renamed version, this way Skype received files would not contain lots of obsolete files received from other people which makes finding the last received file even more difficult.

I'm not sure why this happens for you, but I have several files with the same name (DxDiag.txt) saved in my "My Skype Received Files" folder. Each has the extra index attached, but when I click on the file in Skype, the correct version opens. This is how it should work.  Links to received/sent files are saved in the local main.db database file, and should point to the correct version.

Hi everyone, If you see in the picture that I posted there are multiple sheets with abbreviated team names (Chel,Spurs,Arsena) and then theres a sheet 1 where I want to store specific data from the team name sheets. In cells X25:Y25 of the picture you will see Aaron Ramsey and a number (7.38) this is the highest rating of the table in X1:Y23. Then there is a table in cells AA1:AB23 this is the top goal scorer for that specific team. This is how all of the sheets are within the project, and in "sheet 1"  I want all of the top goal scorers and highest rated players from each team to be displayed in "sheet 1". Also, it must be automated so if the top goalscorer changes in one sheet for example in "aresena sheet" it changes from alexandre to mesuit ozil then in "sheet 1" it must also change to mesuit ozil. Please let me know and thank you in advance.

My (simplistic) take would be to use an index-match. Assuming row 1 is formatting you could have row 2 be A2 Arsenal, B2 =index(Arsena!x:y,Match(Max(Arsena!Y:Y),Arsena!E:E,0),1) C2 =INDEX(Arsena!X:Y,MATCH(MAX(Arsena!Y:Y),Arsena!Y:Y,0),2)  Then for the next row do the same but with the name of the next tab swapped as appropriate  If you are curious what is going on "under the hood" first I find the max number in the data column (Y), and then use match to find out how far down the column that value is.  I then use the index to pull the name next to that column.  A vlookup can't look left, but a combination of Index and Match can. Thanks, Aaron

Hi,  Try this  1. In sheet1, list down all team names starting from cell A2 and going all the way downwards.  Ensure that the spellings here match the spellings of your tab names 2. In cell B2, enter this formula and copy down  =INDIRECT("'"&A2&"'!X25")  Repeat step 2 for bring over data from other cells as well.  Just change the reference to Y25 etc.

John, That is a cool solution, but did you catch the op's request to have the sheet update to the largest value on the original sheet?  So ifY27 becomes larger than Y25, he would want X27 and Y 27 to display, not X25 and Y25. I'd love to see your solution updated for that though! Thanks, Aaron

I have a table of data. It is several hundred rows. I show the min, max and mean of a particular column. Is there a way, in addition to getting the answer, to highlight (different color or background) where it is in the column? It would save time trying to find it. Thanks.

Conditional formatting>Highlight Cell rules>Equal to in the box that opens up, put the cell reference of the cell with your min/max/mean displayed. So if you have your min in E42 and your max in E44, you would put E42 in your condition, set highlight to red, then do it again and put E44 in your condition and set highlight to yellow, etc.  I just verified that conditional formatting can display different formats for different rules. Hope it helps, Aaron

Aaron, Thank you for your reply. However, apparently I was not clear in what I am trying to do. Your solution does highlight the number in the Max or Min cell. What I would like to do (if possible) is highlight the answer in the data column where it appears. For example, if the Min is 324 I would like that number highlighted in the data table so it won't be hard to find.

I think Aaron means, in the cells in the column with numbers, add three conditional formatting rules to each cell. You can create the rules in one cell and then copy...paste special...formats to the other cells in the column.   One rule checks if the cell's value is equal to the cell that contains the MIN of the column and applies the color; the second rule checks if the cell's value is equal to the cell that contains the MAX of the column and applies that color; the third does the same for the average.  So only two to three cells would be colored in the column of numbers.
What cells did you apply the conditional formatting to? If you didn't apply the formatting to the area you want to have highlighted, it won't highlight that area. Thanks, Aaron

Despite appearances, recent versions don't permit you to save the view or zoom with a document. All documents open in Print Layout view at whatever Zoom you last used. (There is a recent bug whereby all documents open in Web Layout view, but that is not the norm.) The "Allow opening a document in Draft view" setting is a holdover for previous versions and has no effect in Word 2013 and above.

Hi Andrew,  Regina is right. There is no out of the box way to open Word newly created files in Draft View automatically. We suggest you vote this UserVoice:  I want to open new blank documents and old documents in View=Draft, not View=PrintA. This is the best way to make our products and services better for you and others. If you are familiar with Macros, you can follow Jay's suggestion or StefanRobert’s suggestion in this thread to approach it.  Thanks, RenaAlfred

To force a particular view on all documents, you will have to use a macro. This is actually true in all versions of Word.  To save the view with the document, as older versions of Word could do, you will have to use an add-in created by MVP Jay Freedman. Download SaveView2013.zip from his web site at https://jay-freedman.info/.

The issue is technically not a Skype issue, it is a Microsoft account issue.  Skype Customer Service would not be able to resolve the problem.  The information requested is used for account and age verification. If you choose to use alternate information, it is best to recall that information, should it be asked again.  In this instance, you chose invalid or minor information, which signifies that a minor may be the current owner of the account.  The date requirement is used to be compliant with COPPA [techtarget.com] and similar child protection laws, to ensure authorized use of the account by a minor with parental consent.   Adults who are not minors, can prove they are adults, resolving the issue.  This is enforced on all Microsoft Accounts regardless of the services used.  Methods of proving you are an adult are covered here.

Hi Rebecca,   Word 2016 for Mac also has those functions:   Regarding “kerning of letters”, you can refer to the following article to do so: Change the line spacing in Word 2016 for Mac.   About “shifting text boxes”, you can refer to the articles: Snap objects to a grid in Word 2016 for Mac Align objects in Word 2016 for Mac   Regards FraserMegan

What the contextual Ribbon for Publishing Layout View in prior versions does provide is a check box tool for turning kerning  On/Off, but there is no manual kerning in any version of Word... perhaps you're thinking of the Character Spacing tool which does provide incremental spinner buttons as well as editable value boxes.?  At any rate, neither is included on the Ribbon in Office 2016. However, both are available as they always have been in their home location: Format> Font - Advanced. I see no option to add either to the QAT but I'm not certain whether they can be added to the Ribbon.  In Word 2016, objects can be nudged in 1/100" increments by holding Command+Control while tapping an Arrow key. Also, the Grid which controls the standard nudging increment can be modified [Word> Preferences - Edit - Grid Options].  Word 2011 is at the end of its life cycle. I have no idea what type of projects are involved, but based on your use of the term novice it may be worth looking at page layout programs. They are object-oriented, whereas Word is not.

Hi all. I'm trying to get a formula going and I think COUNTIF is the right one, but it's just not working. I'm trying to get the result of the number of cells in column D that contains text if the corresponding cell in column A also contains text / is not blank. I'm using =COUNTIF(Column D,(Column A<>"")) but it's resulting in 0 which I know is incorrect. I tried =COUNTIF(Column D,(Column A"<>"&"")) but it tells me there's an error with the formula that doesn't work. What is missing from my COUNTIF formula? Or am I using the wrong type of formula? Thanks Jeffrey
To check two different ranges, use COUNTIFS. For example:  =COUNTIFS(D1:D100,"<>",A1:A100,"<>")
Perfect! Thanks.

The pre-installed Skype application (UWP) on Windows 10 can't start itself, and can't register itself to be started automatically unlike the classic version of Skype. I'm trying to count a range of values, for instance A1:A10, but not count any rows that are hidden in that range. Is there a formula, to NOT count the hidden row? Thanks, Deborah J.

Depends on what you want to do. I've included two scenarios here:  1. The cells in your range are all numbers: =AGGREGATE(2,5,A1:A10).  This will count the number of cells with numbers while only ignoring hidden rows. Any cells with error values or other aggregate functions will still be counted.  2. The cells in your range contain both numbers and text: =AGGREGATE(3,5,A1:A10)  This will count the number of cells that are not blank while only ignoring hidden rows. Any cells with error values or other aggregate functions will still be counted.  Hope this helps.
=SUBTOTAL(102, A1:A10)  The 102 tells it to ignore hidden values in the count. Use just 2 to include hidden values in the count.
I would use:  =SUBTOTAL(103;D4:D10)

I wish to save a backup copy of XL files (to the same folder on C drive as the base file) when I do an update thereto and save the file. I am not referring to Autosave.

When you say not referring to Autosave" I am not sure if you mean the Auto Recover or AutoBackup. There is a description of AutoBackup at the following link. (Go down towards the end of the page under heading "AutoBackup")    https://www.online-tech-tips.com/ms-office-tips/excel-autorecover-and-automatic-backup/  However, the above method overwrites the previous backups and if this is not what you require and you want to keep several versions of backups then you will need to change the document to a Macro Enabled Workbook and use the Save Event VBA code below.   To install the VBA Event code:  Now when the workbook is saved, if changes have been made since opening,  then a backup file will be created in the same folder as the master. If no changes then the file will save as normal but no backup will be created. The backup File Name is in the format  Filename yyyy-mm-dd hh mm ss.xlsm The reverse date with year first is used so the file names can be sorted. All 2 digit months, days, hours, minutes and seconds are used because sorting is based on text and this ensures that sorting occurs correctly.  If the User selects "Save As" then the backup code is not implemented and allows the user to create a file name of choice. ie the user might select a backup version and the use Save As to replace the master copy.  Feel free to get back to me if any problems.   Copy all of the code below into the VBA editor.   Private Sub Workbook_BeforeSave(ByVal SaveAsUI As Boolean, Cancel As Boolean)         Dim strBackupName As String         'If user selects "Save As" then the code for backup does not run so that user     'can select a backup and then save to whatever name is required     If SaveAsUI = False Then         'Only run backup code if change made. Otherwise Save simply saves without backup         If ActiveWorkbook.Saved = False Then             On Error GoTo ReEnableEvents                         Application.EnableEvents = False    'Suppress recursive calls to Save event                         ThisWorkbook.Save       'Save normally                         'Create backup filename using date and time             'Colons invalid in file name and hense colons replaced with spaces in time portion             strBackupName = Left(ThisWorkbook.FullName, InStrRev(ThisWorkbook.FullName, ".xlsm") - 1) _                             & " " & Format(Now, "yyyy-mm-dd hh mm ss") _                             & ".xlsm"                         ThisWorkbook.SaveCopyAs Filename:=strBackupName         End If     End If     ReEnableEvents:     If Err.Number <> 0 Then         MsgBox "Error occurred in ThisWorkbook module, Private Sub Workbook_BeforeSave"     End If         Application.EnableEvents = True End Sub

Thanks MicheleMac, I meant"... not referring to AutoRecover" when I said "... Autosave".  AutoBackup was exactly what I was looking for.  The detailed VBA info you provided is much appreciated also - very worthwhile.

There are several possible fixes mentioned #1 - Disable all Antimalware and firewalls, especially 3rd part ones. Make sure they are turned back on after the update is done. Try running the update. If that didn't work try #2 - restart all Windows services associated with Windows Update: - in Start Menu search for "CMD" - right click on it and select "Run as Administrator" - in the "Command Prompt" window enter the following commands one at a time net stop bits net stop wuauserv net stop appidsvc net stop cryptsvc - enter the following commands to rename the update install folders Ren %systemroot%SoftwareDistribution SoftwareDistribution.bak Ren %systemroot%system32catroot2 catroot2.bak (wait a while after the fix is complete and you are sure it is working, then come back and delete these folders, which at that point are just wasting space.) - restart the update services net start bits net start wuauserv net start appidsvc net start cryptsvc Now try update As well, this is a "voodoo fix". Somehow I have solved it. This problem only appeared after updating Office recently.   I went to the properties of a file saved as .ppsx which would open in power point in the edit mode instead of opening as a slide show. In the properties I went to Change how it opens then clicked on Power Point and clicked apply and OK. I saw that the icon had changed slightly and saw that the icons of all my .ppsx files had slightly changed and all the .ppsx files now open as a slide show and no longer in PP as an edit file.   Don’t know what happened but think that when you work in Power Point and save the file as a.ppsx it really does not save it as a.ppsx but as a .pptx (as it says it must in the Options in the PP program!!) by changing how it opens afterwards it has magically adopted the.ppsx and changed all the files with that suffix to open as shows!  Think it bypasses the glitch in the actual programme where it states in Options – Save that it must save as a presentation with no alternative such as a show.  In Power Point click on File then on Options and then on Save . There it says "save files in this format" there are four or five options but all are Presentations and there is no option to select anything else. Although when you select Power Point Show when you save the file it subliminaly saves it as a Presentation as the Options lays down. In the properties of the file you select Poer Point again as the program to open the file , appl and OK and it accepts the .ppsx suffix (and all similar ones on your PC.

My brother gave me his fairly new laptop recently and I need to use Microsoft Word. When I go to open Word (2016) at the very top reads : SUNSCRIPTION EXPIRED : most of the features of WORD have been disabled; and gives me the option to reactivate. I click reactivate and there are three option I can choose from buy, enter key or sign in. I click enter key and for some reason the zero's in my product key do not come up on screen therefore it will not let me enter the product key info. I can enter all the other number expect the zero's. If I go to sign in it says the product is not associated with my account. The other problem I'm having is if I go to help it says: A world wide web browser such as Window Internet Explorer is required to use this feature and I have internet explorer up and running. My question is can I reactivate Word just by using the product key, and if so why can't I enter all the number in the product key?

Hi,  Product Keys do not contain 0s or Os  Those used are: 2346789BCDFGHJKMPQRTVWXY  Those unused are: 015AEILNOSUZ  And if you decide to try to use the Windows Product Key, it is not the Product Key to use for Office. Office has to be bought and paid for separately.  Cheers.

The message referring to a subscription would indicate this is an Office 365 installation which requires renewal on a monthly or yearly basis.  As Michael says this "product key" is not the Windows Activation key but is the same format (5 x 5 alphanumeric characters)and has no zero or "O" character in it.  If it is an Office 365 subscription then it is almost certainly based on his Microsoft Account login and without those credentials you would not be able to renew it hence the "not associated" message, he has the subscription not you. You would have to buy your own subscription and reinstall Office from your login.  Generally speaking the advice when getting a second hand computer is to Reset Windows completely and remove anything installed after it factory load.

I am trying to figure I way I can share auto text entries with the rest of my faculty. Ideally this would be automatically updateable for everyone as I make changes to them . I can already share documents via Word online so one thought was to have my autotext entries fed onto the page of a shared document but I would have no idea if that is possible without copying and pasting manually.

Hi Brian,  Making your Autotext entries live and shareable is a great idea. However Autotext entries are stored as building blocks.  To create a new entry, we will need to use the Create New Buiding Block dialog box. Please note that Quick Parts is necessary to save the selection to the AutoText Gallery. As of today, Quick parts is not available in Word Online.  We suggest that you send your feedback/ideas on this link so that this feature in be considered in future updates in Word Online.  Feel free to post in the Community if you have additional concerns.

AutoText entries are stored in templates. By default, they are stored in the Normal template, Normal.dotm. Only AutoText entries stored in Normal.dotm will generate AutoComplete tips, but they can be stored in any template.  You can create a special template that users can load as an add-in: if the template is stored in Word's Startup folder, it will be loaded at startup, and AutoText entries in the template will be available to all documents.  If users want to be able to take advantage of AutoComplete, they can move the AutoText entries from the add-in to Normal.dotm using the Building Blocks Organizer. Select any entry, click on Edit Properties, and, in the Save in dropdown, change the location from the add-in to Normal.dotm.

Hello I would like some help with conditional formatting as what I am looking for has a few variables I have  a table  Column A list of names  Columns C- M are blank but sometimes have a "Y" in the cell. What I am wanting is to highlight the cells in columns C-M if there is a "Y" within the cell, but only when the cell in column B which is in the same row has been left blank.   Thanks Michelle

Hi Michelle,  Select columns C to M. In Home menu click Conditional Formatting and then New Rule In the window that opens click Use a formula to determine which cells to format Then put this formula:  =AND($B1="",COUNTA($B1:$M1))  Choose the color you want to color the cells. We are using a large workbook with multiple sheets to capture similar and add new data (different purposes). There are 3 columns (Person's Name, Agency, Topic) that we would like linked across 2 sheets and then be able to add, change or sort data in each one while maintaining the data integrity of the row.   Dummy Data Example 1st sheet: Participants Name        Agency       Topic             Comments         Priority         Contact # Snoopy     Doghouse    Animals          Smells Funny       3 Mickey      Disney         Mice               Catch                 1   2nd Sheet:  Calendar Name        Agency       Topic             Contacted         Status                     Dates Available Snoopy     Doghouse    Animals          Yes                  Arriving Friday Mickey      Disney         Mice                No                 Unknown   I can link the first 3 columns, but if we add data to the others and then sort the 1st sheet, the data linked becomes mismatched with the data entered for each person on the 2nd sheet .  Is there anyway to prevent this while allowing the data to be sorted?   Thanks, Lisa

The value in A2 ("Snoopy") of the Calendar sheet needs to be manually entered.  This can be done using a Data Validation list which refers to column A of the Participants sheet.  Columns B & C in the Calendar sheet need to be formulas like this: In B2: =VLOOKUP($A2,Participants!$A:$C,COLUMN(Participants!$B$1),FALSE) In C2: =VLOOKUP($A2,Participants!$A:$C,COLUMN(Participants!$C$1),FALSE)  That way if the Participants sheet is sorted the Calendar sheet will still look up the correct data.  Hope this helps.  Emily

I will play with that and see how it works.  I was trying to work with VLookup, but didn't know about keeping the first column unlinked. Bad aspect is this is really large, so the name column could potentially have 10,000+ entries...   Thanks,  Lisa
That worked great! Main caveat really is the first column. By accident we had 2 names that were the same, but the values still matched up on both sheets. Thank you! Lisa

=COUNTIF(Participants!$A:$A,$A1)>1  This will show as TRUE if there is a duplicate, or you could put the formula into a Conditional Formatting rule to highlight any duplicates that need to be checked.  Cheers Emily

I have a jpg of a caricature drawing, and I would like to convert it back to a drawing.  I remember doing this some time ago (probably an earlier version of PowerPoint), but I can't seem to remember how in Office 2010.  I thought it was "Edit Drawing" "Edit points", or something, but I can't find the command now.  Can anyone remind me how this is done in Office 2010?  I also have 2013 if necessary. Thanks,

PowerPoint's never been able to convert raster images (like your JPG) to vector.   Raster = a collection of variously colored dots that happen to look like a picture Vector = mathematically defined lines/text/shapes that make up a picture  PowerPoint and many other programs can convert vector graphics to raster but it takes a tracing program to go the other way.  PowerPoint doesn't do it ... sorry.
I'm not familure with your terms.  Can I convert a picture to line art in Power Point?
Kevin is basically saying this has never been possible in PPt.  One of the artistic effects in PPT may give a similar effect but it is still a raster image.

I recently contacted the help desk for Office 2016 for the Mac about changing the font sizes in the Navigation Pane and in the Comment balloons. I could not figure out a way to do this from within the Navigation Pane or the Review menu.  I tried several levels of Microsoft Support but we couldn’t make it work. After hanging up, I kept trying for a while and here’s is what finally worked:  Navigation Pane:  Have the Navigation Pane open. Select Format/Styles from the Word menu. Choose “Document Map” style under the Styles pull-down menu. Choose the styles/fonts/sizes that you want. Click Apply.  Comment Balloons:  Have comment balloons displayed and then highlight some text from any comment. Select Format/Styles from the Word menu. Choose the ‘Comment Text’ style. Make your changes and then click Apply. This is new to me but it seems to work every time. I would appreciate seeing if others can validate this approach.

At least in WinWord, you have to modify not only Comment Text but also Balloon Text to ensure that text inside comments have the formatting you want. (Modifying the Document Map style does not work at all in recent versions of WinWord. It did work in the Document Map, the predecessor of the Navigation pane.)

It would seem to me that you've already validated these methods, yourself :-)  I have no idea what was suggested by the support folks you spoke with, but the methods you've described aren't just one way, they're the only way... IOW, that's what should have been suggested to begin with.  The one point that differs is that it is not necessary to open the Navigation Pane or have any Comments in a document in order to modify the Styles which determine their formatting. The Styles can be modified at any time, including when you start in a new blank document. It's just that the Styles are a bit easier to locate if they are in use. If not currently in use you have to select All Styles in the dialog window, then find those you want in a rather lengthy list.
This doesn't seem to be working for me.  For some reason the font in the Document Map doesn't change when I alter the Document Map style.
Which version of Word are you running? Note that the Navigation pane can't be customized (that only worked with the old Document Map in older versions of Word for Windows).
Thanks for the response David.   Using 2016 for mac.   So changing the Document Map style doesn't change how the text appears in the navigation pane?  Not sure I quite follow.

As I wrote, the Document Map style controlled the appearance of entries in the Document Map in older versions of Word. The appearance of entries in the Navigation pane can't be customized at all. (The Document Map style exists only for backward compatibility reasons.)  That is how it works in Windows versions of Word. We will have to wait for someone to confirm how it works in Word 2016 for Mac.
OK, got it.  Thanks.

Hello, If I have a pptx file that has 2 custom shows: Show 1: slides 1 and 3 Show 2: slides 2 and 3 How can I save Show 1 into a new pptx file that has slides 1 and 3 from the original file? Many thanks. Keith
Simplest approach:  Save a copy of your presentation and delete the slides you don't need.

Hi James, I think I am going to try to code this, as the presentation is around 70 slides, and I have 4 Custom Shows therein. I can share any ideas that I come up with as I try to do this, if that's useful. Thanks. Keith
Bear in mind that Custom Shows may not be in the same slide order as the original and may have repeated slides. Makes the code more difficult if you want to include this or add as an option.

Hi Susan,  That's interesting, but I never have those 2 situations, so it should not affect my code. (Didn't there used to be a way to mark answers as helpful, even if they did not resolve your issue? I can't find that button at the moment.)  Many thanks.  Keith

Have a go with this.  It'll save the slides from each of your custom shows out to a separate presentation.  Watch out for linebreaks that the forum editor "helpfully" introduces. Option Explicit  Sub WhoIsInSlideShow()          Dim oPres As Presentation     Dim oCopyPres As Presentation     Dim lShowNum As Long     Dim x As Long          Set oPres = ActivePresentation          With oPres         ' Don't do anything if there are no custom shows!         If .SlideShowSettings.NamedSlideShows.Count > 0 Then                      ' We have shows; work with each of them in turn:             For lShowNum = 1 To .SlideShowSettings.NamedSlideShows.Count                                  oPres.SaveCopyAs oPres.Path & "\" & "SHOW_" & CStr(lShowNum) & "_" & oPres.Name                 Set oCopyPres = Presentations.Open(oPres.Path & "\" & "SHOW_" & CStr(lShowNum) & "_" & oPres.Name)                                           With oCopyPres                     For x = .Slides.Count To 1 Step -1                         ' is this slide part of the current custom show?                         ' if not, delete it                         If Not IsInCustomShow(.Slides(x).SlideID, lShowNum) Then                             .Slides(x).Delete                         End If                     Next                     .Save                     '.Close                 End With    ' copy presentation                              Next    ' custom show         End If  ' has custom shows     End With   ' oPres, current presentation  End Sub  Function IsInCustomShow(lSlideID As Long, lShowNum As Long) As Boolean     Dim x As Long     For x = 1 To UBound(ActivePresentation.SlideShowSettings.NamedSlideShows(lShowNum).SlideIDs)         If lSlideID = ActivePresentation.SlideShowSettings.NamedSlideShows(lShowNum).SlideIDs(x) Then             IsInCustomShow = True             Exit Function         End If     Next End Function

MS Excel: Function that returns Last Modified date for Workbook Looking to add a cell that show the last time I open or worked on the workbook. Is this possible? Thanks, Eric

Hi Eric,   You can create a macro based on the article you provided to send back the last modified time in your workbook. Since you are using Excel 2016 for Mac, I will show you how to do it on Mac.   1. Go to Develop tab, if you don't have it, go to Excel > Preference > Ribbon > check the Develop tab. Then click Visual Basic button.    2. Right click ThisWorkbook and choose Insert > Module.   3. In the VB editor, insert VB script:   Function LastModified() as Date         LastModified = ActiveWorkbook.BuiltinDocumentProperties("Last Save Time")   End Function   4. Close VB editor and save the workbook as a macro-enabled workbook, open the workbook again, in the cell you want to display the last modified time, insert =lastmodified(), if the time doesn't displayed as expect, you can change the cell format to Date or Time.   Meanwhile, you can add another macro to skip the step of insert formula manually.   Follow the steps 1,2 mentioned above to create a new module, type in the following script:   Sub formula()       Range("C4").formula = "=lastmodified()"   End Sub   Click Macros under Develop tab, select the macro and click Options, then assign a shortcut key to the macro.    Next time when you open the workbook, you can just use the shortcut key to show the last modified time to the cell you want.   Regards, TiskyRicardo

In Microsoft excel how do you lookup a certain value in a row and then look up another value in that row and then count the amount of times that second value appears in the row is the question. So in other words, the first value identifies the row the second value identifies what to look for in that row then instead of returning that exact value it returns the amount of times that value shows up in the specific row.  Example: So lets say you have a workweek sheet and a workweek summary sheet. On the workweek sheet it highlights the workers and the work done at different times during the day. On the summary Sheet it uses that data to tell you who (Value 1)  did what assignment (Value 2) and how many times they did it (Adding it). Of course that person would be doing different things during the day so it needs to be able to tell the difference (case sensitive). It does not need to tell you what time they did it since its based on a week that would be unnecessary data it just needs to tell you how many times they did a assignment during that week. And since persons may change through out the week once you type in a name to search and work assignment it should auto change its total(automated system i am looking for) .  Example code that didn't work but this is what I came up with:  =MATCH(Summary!$G$2,INDEX(Tuesday!$B$2:$E$58,MATCH(Summary!A5,Tuesday!$A$2:$A$58),)) Summary!A5 = Would be the person I look for in a row. this is a vertical lookup of names ( summary sheet ) Summary!$G$2 = Would be the assignment to look for on the workweek sheet but this ( text to look at ) is on the ( summary sheet ) Tuesday!$B$2:$E$58 = Would be the assignments to search through ( workweek sheet ) Tuesday!$A$2:$A$58 = Would be the row of names to search through ( workweek sheet ) Its like a two way lookup but on the second look up it looks at the whole row and identifies all the matching values/text in the row and adds the amount of times they show up.
Hi,  Share the link from where I can download your workbook.  Also show the expected result there.

Formula in cell D1:  =SUMPRODUCT(--(EXACT(INDEX($B$2:$O$58,MATCH(A1,$A$2:$A$58,0),),B1)))   This identifies the row in column A which matces the cell A1 name. And then from that row ie. B2:O2 it counts the number of times "As3" appears. And this is a case-sensitive match so that the 2 occurrences of "as3" (marked in red font) are not counted.  In case you do not want case-sensitive then use the below formula entered in cell C1:  =SUMPRODUCT(--(INDEX($B$2:$O$58,MATCH(A1,$A$2:$A$58,0),)=B1))   Please adjust the range / sheet names ... the above is illustrated in the same sheet for convenience. In case this is your requirement ...   Regards, Harry Tandon www.globaliconnect.com

Did you set the hard disk mode to IDE?  In order to install Windows XP on the partition you created, you will need to boot into your BIOS and set the hard disk mode to IDE. -------------------------------------------- After you have set the hard disk IDE mode, you can proceed to install Windows XP on the partition you created; Insert your Windows XP CD, then restart your computer. When prompted to boot from the CD, do so. This requires pressing any key on your keyboard. Windows XP will go through its setup process. Once you arrive at the Welcome Setup, press Enter on your keyboard to begin the setup process Press F8 on your keyboard to accept the license agreement Select the partition Select Format the partition using the NTFS file system Press F on your keyboard to begin the formatting. Installation files will now be copied to your hard disk Your system will be restarted, Windows XP setup will continue ---------------------------------------------- After Windows XP installs successfully, you will not be able to boot into Windows 7. This is where the recovery disc for Windows 7 comes in. 1. Put the Windows 7 Recovery disc installation disc into the disc drive, and then start the computer. 2. Press a key when the message indicating "Press any key to boot from CD or DVD …". appears. 3. Select a language, a time, a currency, and a keyboard or another input method, and then click Next. 4. Click Repair your computer. 5. Click the operating system that you want to repair, and then click Next. 6. In the System Recovery Options dialog box, click Command Prompt. 7. Type sfc /scannow, and then press ENTER. -------------------------------------------- After you have repaired your Windows 7 installation and try to boot it, you will notice that Windows 7 does not boot. Boot into the BIOS again and set the hard disk mode to SATA. You will now be able to boot into Windows 7 again. ------------------------------------------- After doing that, download EasyBCD and add a boot entry for Windows XP to the Windows 7 boot manager; EasyBCD by NeoSmart Technologies would be your answer, it provides a graphical front end to the BCDEdit Command line that makes it easy for you to define start-up settings and edit boot entries on the new Windowsboot manager. http://neosmart.net/dl.php?id=1 ------------------------------------------ The next step now is make it possible for Windows 7 to boot in IDE mode. Here are the instructions for doing that: http://www.vistax64.com/general-discussion/271218-switch-ahci-ide-tutorial-howto.html Welcome all , so let me explain I installed Windows 7 With AHCI set from Bios , but after that i wanted to use ide (becose it boots faster) and when i set Ide from Bios , the windows 7 loading screan camed upp and BSOD (Blue screen of death) with an error code 0x0000005B , i tryed the regedit trick by setting in the "HKEY_LOCAL_MACHINESystemCurrentControlSetServicesMsahci" and then in the right pan the START value from 0 i set it to 1 and it supposed to be working but it was a failiure , it still did the Bsod and i was so pissed of , i wanted to make it work ... AND I DID IT !  Here are the pases : 1) I assume u have installed Windows Vista or Windows 7 with AHCI set from BIOS ! 2) Download my registry fix (to add the ide keys to regeditor) simply apply the key 3) Now the manually regedit part Go to :  HKEY_LOCAL_MACHINE_System_CurrentControlSet_Services_Msahci HKEY_LOCAL_MACHINE_System_CurrentControlSet_Services_iaStor HKEY_LOCAL_MACHINE_System_CurrentControlSet_Services_iaStorV  And in thease three keys in the right pan u will find a key named "START" change at all three (Msahci,iaStor,iaStorV) values from 0 To 1 Now navigate to HKEY_LOCAL_MACHINE_System_CurrentControlSet_Services_PciIde ,then change the start value to "0"    4) Now u are allmost done , restart your computer/laptop , and go to Bios and set from AHCI to IDE !!! , save settings in Bios and restart  5)Windows will be loading , and VOILA !!! NO BSOD !!! , windows Vista/Seven will install new Ide drivers and u will see in windows device manager that you dont have AHCI drivers anymore , u have Ide drivers ! 6)It will prompt for another restart , just restart it and u will be happy ---------------------------------  The first option I would recommend, if you really need to run Windows XP is to use Windows Virtual PC with Windows XP Mode, you will need to upgrade to Windows 7 Professional or Ultimate in order to gain access to Windows XP Mode. Here is the code I am using :   Range("P2").Select     ActiveCell.FormulaR1C1 = _         "=VLOOKUP(F2,'Supplier list'!A:B,2,0)" When the formula appears in my workbook it gives me =VLOOKUP('F2','Supplier list'!A:(B),2,0) The  ' ' around the cell ref and the ( ) around the B in my table array are causing the formula to brings back #NAME? Change the 2nd line to  ActiveCell.Formula = "=VLOOKUP(F2,'Supplier list'!A:B,2,0)"
'--- Jim Cone Portland, Oregon USA https://goo.gl/IUQUN2 (Dropbox) (free & commercial excel add-ins & workbooks)

Just to add to the wonderful solutions already provided, the problem is that you specified the argument to your VBA functions would be in R1C1 format and then provided an A1 formatted formula.   the solutions used just the Formula function which looks for an A1 formatted formula.  If however, you wanted to use FormulaR1C1 then you could have done this: Sub abc() Range("P2").Select ActiveCell.FormulaR1C1 = _         "=VLOOKUP(RC[-10],'Supplier list'!C[-15]:C[-14],2,0)" End Sub   that produces the formula  =VLOOKUP(F2,'Supplier list'!A:B,2,0)  in cell P2.   Not that the cell references in the result are relative as you originally appeared to want.   -- Regards, James Ogilvy
